commentBody:
@Deb
@Fionatimes

The mark of a brilliant clue is when it contains just the right amount of quirk to point you immediately at the answer even though you're entirely unfamiliar with the clue's specific content and because you totally gut grok its vibe.

Who else but Gorey would hatch such a title?

@Steven M.

I wish I had a nickel for every hour I spend trying to get 18-year-old Tennessee students to understand limiting reactants.

I really wish I did.  That's just about all they paid for the arts and sciences.

@Boris

And I wish the US Weekly solvers would stay where the puzzles consistently make them feel just as clever as they like, rather than whining about NYT Saturday puzzles that put up a tiny bit of a fight ;)

Great one from KAC, btw!

@SP
I would say the opposite. Yesterday was an easy Friday and much better for new solvers to stick with. It still took me about 50 minutes.

I found todays level of difficulty is just irritating. I’m not exaggerating when I say there is not a single clue that I thought was clever. Just grudging acceptance that they could fit the answers. Enjoyable day for the experienced folks, and that’s fine, but not worth sticking with. And I spent nearly an hour doing a slow reveal with the help to still get as many as I could without the help.

@Francis

"hard enough to please almost everyone here"

He he

@Francis

Yeah, you're not hard enough to make me come.

(you sure set me up for this, didn't you)

@Andrzej

You're not trying*

D'oh. What a Freudian slip! Totally accidental.

@Andrzej

That's the same square, and pretty much the same experience i had with that square.  Mentally running, the alphabet, somehow the R just felt right.

I would imagine that will be a much commented on cross.

@Andrzej

Alphabet run on same square.

SE first to fall, then SW, NW, center (except that one square), and finally NE.

@Matt

Us in the first world are free to waste our time however we wish 🤷🏽

Ultimately I don't see how we can objectively evaluate fair and unfair puzzle content given how different people are and how different the things they know and don't know may be. In attempting to do that you will end up judging people by what they learned or didn't learn over the course of their complex lives, and that's just something the egalitarian empath element of me can't accept.

@Ιασων

Does it look to you like I'm good at compromising? 🤣

¡Zeener neener Elea shmelea!

@Heidi
The same clue with Crawford or Brinkley is a Monday clue.

I’ve no idea what Cars refers to there.

@The X-Phile

Good analysis on the UCLA example.  

That's exactly how it played out for me.  It was November, college football season.  Washington and UCLA were in the same division.

@LBG

"Kidney stONE" would have made for a nice answer to "Channel blocker", if it had fit.

Future constructors take note.

@Jane Wheelaghan

I was thinking of asking who all here knew RIG VEDA with few or no crosses.  

I needed every one of them.

@Jeff B MD
SOAP STARS was nice long toehold for me too, as a daytime drama fan for more than 60 years.
This was an excellent Saturday puzzle.

@JJJJ

Yep, that was the obvious answer, and I fell for it, too.
A nice little example of a clever Saturday misdirect.

@Vaer

PAULINA is Czech, no???

But not a problem. How many models are there named "Porizkova"?

@Times Rita

Great post.  Captures my feelings last weekend quite nicely.

I sometimes try to put on a brave front, but dejection really is the right word when it happens?  "Why couldn't I have seen the clue in that light while I was trying to solve it?"

@Michael

It's a walk taken while one is on the water, is it not? 

A bit of flexibility is required of solvers. Nothing misleading or inaccurate about the clue.

@Michael

Misleading, but not inaccurate.  It just requires an extra level of thinking.
Such intentionally misleading clues are called "misdirects" here in Crosslandia.

@Esmerelda

I was torn on the new kea-loa of AVIARIES - ApIARIES ---- bees are fliers, too!
Thus I had APO____ for 2 down and was thinking ApOstle as the original side hustle sales job. But surely Forbes wouldn't be that irreverent.

@Nick 

That was one of the few "gimmes" for me. 

 One of the many things my wife and I  had in common was an appreciation for this author, which I discovered when I saw "Amphigorey" in her bookcase shortly after we met.

@Nick

I looked up nothing 🤷🏽

Ano no, I didn't know most of today's trivia.

@Mean Old Lady
Yeah, well, I kept thinking it couldn't be Atlanta because southern meccas mean Florida, don't they?

Of course, "North" meant Dalhonega to me for a long, long time.

@Marcy

There really are no inviolable rules in crosswords, I don't think.  Certainly not in the clue.

In fact, quite often the same puzzle will use the same clue two or three times.

@Vaer

To complicate matters, there are those who think that Ronan Farrow is actually the biological child of Mia Farrow and Frank Sinatra.  (He does look more like Frank than Woody, and Mia has herself said that it was possible.)

O, Hollywood gossip, how I wish you would stay out of my brain.

@E

SEA-TAC is classic old crossword-ese, but probably feels obscure to you in the UK.
It's short for the Seattle- Tacoma airport in Washington state, known as SEA-TAC since the 1940s.

@Linda Jo 
Yeah that's fair enough, I do get that it is the 'New york' times so obviously there are a lot of USA-centric answers. 

That specific one was the tip of the iceberg for me, I thought that many of the answers and clues in this one were not up to the usual standard of the NYT crossword: I didn't feel great completing it, it wasn't rewarding, and I'd even go as far as to say it felt like a waste of time and I would have been better off not starting it in the first place.

@Cliff Shaw
Bar bets "outdated"?
Ever been in a bar?

@Nancy
LATTE ART very often is a hEART. 

Other people's one liners get posted, but mine not always.

@The X-Phile

Necessarily hard is when I can do it, but you can't.

Unnecessarily hard is when you can do it, and I can't.

@EagleAngle 

It's very normal. There are many like you and I. We are Legion.

I had about 15 guesses when I hit autocheck, and more than half were wrong. But I learned what marlstone is versus aggregate! Cheers.

@SP
I'm sure your advice is excellent, and I am happy to learn new words, like MARLE STONE and REACTANT, but if I had to acquaint myself with trends and celebrities I would never do another crossword!
There are far too many 'celebrities' (never heard of Paulina, or in fact, of her husband, he of The Cars) but I do enjoy solving what I can.

@Charles 
Aren't all crosswords trivia (more or less)?
Brutal clueing is expected on a Saturday, I would be disappointed if there wasn't any!

@Janine

I, too, am confused by the "trivia" charge.

I think in a sense everything is trivial.  On the cosmic scale, the cosmos is trivial.

@The X-Phile
Yeah, Neville has to be mine, too.

"S is for Susan who perished of fits" used to be a favorite. I realize now that Gorey might have meant something medical, which would not be at all funny. But as a youngster I interpreted "fits" to be fits of anger, or temper tantrums. Which I was unfortunately known for. I thought that dramatically dying from one might make my point better than whatever I was doing.

@Brian
You're kidding.
People really say "neurosurg"?
